title: Fix incorrect tuple usage and syntax
body:
Lots of packages use singleton tuple syntax in place of array syntax. `[number]` was previously *almost* compatible with `number[]`, so it slipped through in a lot of places. Now, [with fixed-length tuples](https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/pull/17765), this reliably fails.

The fixed-length tuple also found a couple of errors, in highchart and leaflet. I changed the highchart test to be correctly-typed, although the intent of the test is probably a bit changed. I am 99% sure the test is wrong, though, based on the [highchart documentation](https://www.highcharts.com/docs/chart-concepts/series).

The leaflet test assumes that `LatLng` marks whether altitude was provided in its type, which it does not, so converting a `LatLng` returns `[number, number] | [number, number, number]`, which was previously equivalent to `[number, number]`.

It's relatively simple to add a type parameter `LatLng<T extends number | undefined>`, but it's a big change that's outside the scope of this set of simple fixes.

body:
This adds type hints for builders, commands and their respective
callbacks functions out to seven arity, while leaving the nonspecific
versions for backwards compatibility. This allows
`commandFactory.getOrCreate()` to create fully type hinted callback
signatures, both for the builder and the command.

```js
const command = commandFactory.
  getOrCreate<ResponseType, Arg1Type, Arg2Type>();
```

I also replaced all references to `Q` with `PromiseLike`, and added the
missing `hystrix.promise.implementation` configuration option, which
allows changing the underlying promise implementation.

This allows things like:

```js
const Bluebird = require("bluebird");
HystrixConfig.init({
  "hystrix.promise.implementation": Bluebird
});
(command.execute() as Bluebird<any>).catch(() => true);
```

...although I couldn't figure out how to more elegantly express that
Bluebird type.

title: Fix debounce importing when targeting ECMAScript 2015 modules
body:
Follow up on #21112
The current declaration have the following problems: (That the tests don't catch...)

When importing like:
```ts
import debounce from "debounce";
```
You get 
`@types/debouce/index"' has no default export.`

When importing like:
```ts
import * as debounce from "debounce";
```
You get 
```
 resolves to a non-module entity and cannot be imported using this construct.
```

When importing like:
```ts
import debounce = require("debounce");
```
You don't get inline error in the IDE, but when running tsc you get:
```ts
 TS1202: Import assignment cannot be used when targeting ECMAScript 2015 modules. Consider using 'import * as ns from "mod"', 'import {a} from "mod"', 'import d from "mod"', or another module format instead.
```

The suggested change fixed that issue. i don't know why, i just saw the same pattern in other declarations files

title: [execa] update to v0.8, refactor definitions, fix issue with intersection types
body:
### Changes

- Align types with execa v0.8
- Add JSDoc documentation for everything
- Restructure definitions file based on [chroma-js typings](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/blob/097d2acf711df3ffb7a3df62554769b216876275/types/chroma-js/index.d.ts) to expose function return types such as `ExecaChildProcess`
- Fix being unable to pass a boolean to `shell` option due to an issue with intersection types

The types of the options objects were previously defined like this:
```ts
import { ExecOptions, SpawnOptions, SpawnSyncOptions } from "child_process";
type Options = SpawnOptions & ExecaOptions & ExecOptions;
type SyncOptions = SpawnSyncOptions & ExecaOptions & ExecOptions;
```

The problem lies in the `SpawnOptions & ExecOptions` part. These objects both have a `shell` property, but slightly different definitions:

`SpawnOptions`
```ts
{
  shell?: boolean | string;
}
```

`ExecOptions`
```ts
{
  shell?: string;
}
```
The intersection type of these properties (with `strictNullChecks` enabled) is

```ts

```

I fixed it up and used it everywhere it applies. I also created a type `ShellArray` that does the same thing for `string[]`.
